segments.text: drastic change because it was it was very of course they had that year of interim yeah and you sort of you know i floundered around for that one year and uh but um would you but you were really you more or less kept kept it the way hubert
Or were you somewhere in between the two?

I would have to say I had to be somewhere in between the two, because I recognized that in the position I played, I could not say, there it is, and that's where we're going, because I was not going to be around any length of time to see if we got there.
So it was definitely a period of time where the college wallowed around, and we did the best we could with what we had.
Did you get very much input?
participation from Hubert after he became chancellor?
No, no, no.
And he is not that type of individual.
If you had come up and wanted to get some information, he would be only too glad to provide it.
I can recall, I don't know if you were sitting right there, when we went up on another matter one time, I can't remember exactly what it was, but he
He was very interested in having Cole come up there and work for him.
And I recognized that Cole was the individual that would carry and give the continuity to many of the things in the dean's office.
His experiences date back to when he was a graduate student and worked in the dean's office when we were over there in the Cushing Library building and that type of thing.
But Dean Hubert, who he could have, of course, and explained very nicely, Phil, that he's coming up here.
I want him, period.
After all, that is the chancellor we're talking to.
But he asked my opinion, and I gave him my opinion, and he honored it.
He let him study, and I'm pleased that he did.
I think the college would be in a difficult position if there was not what I call the continuity.
That somebody has the historical background.
And from my interview with Dean Cole, I asked him about that because I have heard from other interviews that a lot of the decision-making goes to him.
And he said that the dean does seek his counsel in a lot of the decisions and usually listens.
And I think that's good because he feels that there is that.
No.
And Hubert always did the same.
As far as when you got up there and you were on his staff,
This guidance was very clear.
That's your area.
You were what Dean Coles, in Dean Coles' position as Dr. Hubert.
Yes, yes.
Which is the Student Affairs.
That's right, the Student Affairs.
And Hubert was very clear and, Bill, that's yours.
You handle it.
If you have need of my assistance, come visit with me.
And I would go to see him on sensitive political things, you know, when state senators wanted their kid to get in and this kind of thing.
Generally speaking, it was very interesting.

You would tell them to go blow it, and stand behind you, and Prescott would stand behind you, and Calhoun would stand behind you, and we would tell them, sorry, but that isn't the way the university operates.
At other times, there were other political decisions that never reached the confrontation type of thing, but were done in a
A typical style.
It was done all behind, sub rosa.
And you were presented with what the French called fait accompli.
Okay.
How do you feel that the college was perceived by outsiders at the time?
And by outsiders, I mean maybe within Texas A&M or even beyond.
Was there... College of Education, notoriously.
Everyone that I've been associated with.
They're usually looked down upon by the colleges of liberal arts.
We were more fortunate here.
There is still that.
And I see evidences of it creeping back up again.
And the state, of course, is assisting in that kind of putting it down type of thing.
But the reason I say I think we were more fortunate, you know the history in that Dean Hubert was the dean of liberal arts.
And he had the opportunity to continue the dean of liberal arts or to continue, help to move over.
And he chose to take over the College of Education, which, of course, gave us a tremendous boost in the eyes of the rest of the faculty.
And he knew where all the skeletons were in most of the colleges, having formed many of the colleges.
So that we rode along very nicely for a fair time.
How we are today, I really do not know.

But of course, the state has taken such a hatchet swing at us that I don't see how we can be counted to be able to hold our heads up and be looked upon by our colleagues as where we think we should be.
Were you instrumental in being this acting dean in the search and the ultimate
selection of Dean Corrigan?
Other than, other than as a member of the college, the search committee was basically given free reign.
Eskimo Monroe, I think, was dean of faculties, and I think he was the chairman of the
or ex officio or something like that.
And it was strictly a decision on the part of that committee, a recommendation.
The faculty were given a voice in it, but the decision basically was one up at that committee level.
I see nothing wrong with that process.
I would prefer to have that type of process than one where a faculty has the sole decision and the university is not involved in it.
I think the university does a good job of bringing in and giving everybody an opportunity to express opinions.
We had some good quality people, excellent people.
One of the perceptions from a faculty member

having worked under both, that when the Corrigan administration took over, there was more opportunities for faculty to, I believe she put it something about being more creative, having an opportunity to expand, whatever.
How do you feel about that?
I would tend to agree in that being Corrigan always has a tendency to encourage an individual to do these things.
the individual faculty member is encouraged to be creative.
His or her opinions are sought.
The other side of the coin is if you have 50 people going in 50 different directions, when do you get the focus?
to this type of thing.
And these are just problems that an administration has to wrestle with.
What is the role of setting the overall arching goal of this type of thing and then fitting into this?
How many years did you work under Dean Corbyn?
He came in 1980.
I retired the first time under, I retired.
He asked me to stay on half the time with him, and I stayed half the time with him until 84, I think, and that's when they asked me to go over to the National.
And you were also very
instrumental in getting that, was it the NK?
Oh, yes.
I've seen your name on all those reports.
That was a big job for you.
That was.
And I was very pleased with the report they had, because we felt that we had a good college of education.
And the visiting team couldn't say enough good things about it.
I believe they're getting ready for another one here pretty soon.
I'm very pleased.
Another set of hands.
OK.
Visions.
And again, I guess because you're not there now, it's hard for you to maybe have a handle on where the college is going.
Have you stayed in touch very much, or do you know?
No.
I'm of the school that I've seen in so many offices where the old guard keeps coming back until they get to be a boring nuisance.
I don't come back.
Rarely do I come back.
I just came back recently from New England.
I brought Dean Corrigan and a couple
sugar maple leaves for them, you know, this kind of thing.
But I don't get in there because I know that there are just a lot of office politics and things and this type of thing, so I just go.
It was a nice way of moving away from it when I was moving into the International for, I don't know, two, three years.
I can't recall how long it was.
And that way I got away from it.
I don't go to the Christmas parties anymore and this kind of thing.
I've done a little bit of art in one of the classes, 653, studying the culture and the climate of the college.
Did that change drastically during your time?
Because, you know, the sex.
We in the college probably had more
women in 69 and 70 than any other college.
It was a doctoral thing.
And I lament the fact that what was our strong support, which was that intelligent young female, has now left and has gone to business and other places.
The strength of the College of Education has always been
the quality of the dedicated females that we at one time attracted, which we do not anymore.
And it's understandable.
The grass is quite a bit greener than some of the other places.
Do you think the pendulum is going to swing back any time?
I hope for the youngsters' sake that it does.
And I don't know what inducements we will give or what delusionments
will have to come before they come back.
But I'm biased in that I think a dedicated teacher gets a reward of the intrinsic award that you get from it that you cannot find in many other types of things.
This is just a garrulous old man, but I feel strongly about it.
Can you talk just for a couple of minutes about any particular highlights
and are perhaps your contribution during your time here.
I'm encountering some reluctance on the part of interviewees to elaborate on their contributions, but an insight, an observation.
You gave me some good anecdotes at the beginning, too.
Is there something that stands out?
Well, that which you take pride in.
I think that which I take pride in is the struggle
enhance the image of the college in the university community.
And you use that medium of exchange, which is the GPR, as the medium of exchange that you can say our students are equal to or better than, this type of thing.
That was a very difficult struggle.
The associate deans

had a group, we called it the academic, no, I really can't recall the name of it, but there was a group that was set up because there was a need for people to come together who were going to actually implement the decisions that the university
APC, or the Academic Programs Committee, which was the president and the vice president, provost now, and all this kind of thing, and the deans.
They would make the policy.
But as is true of most organizations, they didn't really know how to implement it.
And you're not expected to know.
But the associate deans did.
And that was our organization where we fleshed out and implemented
those decisions that were made by the APC.
And it was in that organization that the struggle was, because they were always trying to make it easy for their colleges to get rid of their deadwood.
And we would continually struggle to prevent them from dumping onto this place.
And yet, at the same time, want the opportunity to look at those kids to try to salvage what, in our judgment,
were useful students.
And it's a very sensitive and delicate thing.
And I think it's still going on to a large extent.
And I think Dean Cole has had it made more difficult by our legislators down there.
And I don't know.
In closing, Dr. Lindbacher, is there anything that you would like to add?
add to the different areas that we've talked about, even if they're not even directly related to any of the questions?
Well, the use of the policy committee meeting, either in the archives or in the dean's office.
Hubert's secretary used to be on Peggy Ritchie.
She's still there, and she's given me a lot of those documents.
That, to me, would be, and they're not
generally too thick.
And if you can get them in chronological order, things begin to emerge.
They're just at least their guideposts as to the direction they were going.
It doesn't have all the nuances that you would get from a.
Was it the agendas or the minutes that they would be?
Oh, the minutes.
Oh, the minutes.
The minutes.
The agendas are useful, but the minutes would give you some flavor for the kinds of actions that took place.
I would say that they would be very fruitful areas for
hanging some of these ideas that you have on.

That's right, because what I'm interested in so much, besides the history, because there hasn't been anything since 1967 when Lorraine Roby did the study, but since then nothing has been done as far as the historical, but I'm interested in the perceptions of people and the human part of the college, what really made it
made those things happen, the kinds of personalities, and the interaction of personalities, and how all of that evolved to the great college that there is now.
Well, I mean, what you're after is, I think, the interesting aspects of it.
But I think there needs to be a basic structure that you begin to hang these things on.
Right, exactly.
And maybe it's because I used to enjoy history
You need a historical thread that would take you through.
Now, those were initiated by Dean Hubert, and they continued the same under Dean Corrigan?
To my knowledge, yes, they continued the same.
It's a policy committee group.
I guess now they just call it, is it the normal faculty meeting or department head meeting or whatever?
Department head meeting, maybe that.
I think that's what they call it now.
Department head meeting.
I think so.
Yeah, they called them policy committee meetings at that time.
And that was a weekly?
Weekly, weekly.
And they were legislative.
It, you know, it provided
information and it also provided opportunities for departments to bring up things that were bothering them.

A lot of my interviews, you know, everybody of course relates to the two administrations and even though the Hubert administration is often referred to as autocratic, dictatorial, there's still a lot of that humanness that the people that worked intimately with Hubert were able to perceive that perhaps was not as perceivable.
I think anyone who worked with D. Hubert recognized his ability in the professional area.
He was outstanding as a politician.
He, having worked in the Texas Education Agency, knew the politics in there.
He knew the skeletons.
And he, of course, was a very close friend of Alton Bowen, who became, as you know, the commissioner.
And Alton is, of course,
He was also on our first development council.
I'll be going with him.
I told him last night.
Thank you very, very much, Dr. Limbacher.
I appreciate your insights and hope you'll let me ask you some questions later.
